These are the check-the-work helper functions — the ones a "judge the work itself, not re-audit the whole repo" rule composes. Here are three, from `engine/checks/helpers/line-scanning.mjs`:

**1. `addedLines` — the core check-the-work primitive** (`engine/checks/helpers/line-scanning.mjs:28`)

```js
// Every line the current change ADDED (vs the scoping base) across `files`.
// The "changed lines of the current pull request": a check-the-work rule scans
// these to judge the work itself instead of re-auditing the world, so legacy
// state the change never touched stays quiet.
export function addedLines(ctx, files = ctx.changedFiles) {
  return files.flatMap((f) => ctx.addedLines(f).map((l) => ({ file: f, ...l })));
}
```

**2. `matchingLines` — scan a file set for a pattern** (`engine/checks/helpers/line-scanning.mjs:10`)

```js
// Every line in `files` where `re` matches: [{ file, line, text }], 1-indexed,
// ready to anchor findings. Pass a non-global regex.
export function matchingLines(ctx, files, re) {
  const out = [];
  for (const f of files) {
    const text = ctx.read(f);
    if (text === null) continue;
    text.split('\n').forEach((ln, i) => {
      if (re.test(ln)) out.push({ file: f, line: i + 1, text: ln });
    });
  }
  return out;
}
```

**3. `ruleIdsIn` — introspect declared rule ids in a directory** (`engine/checks/helpers/line-scanning.mjs:36`)

```js
export function ruleIdsIn(ctx, dir) {
  const ids = new Set();
  for (const f of ctx.files) {
    if (dirname(f) !== dir || !f.endsWith('.mjs')) continue;
    if (f.endsWith('/pack.mjs') || f.endsWith('.test.mjs')) continue;
    const src = ctx.read(f);
    if (src === null) continue;
    for (const m of src.matchAll(/\bid:\s*'([a-z][\w-]+)'/g)) ids.add(m[1]);
  }
  return ids;
}
```

The key one is `addedLines` — it's what makes a check "check *the work*" rather than "check the world": it diffs against the merge-base so a rule only judges lines the current change introduced, leaving pre-existing legacy state quiet.

